ExtraaLearn Project by Lucky Ejenavi Salomi ¶

Project Overview¶

Context¶

The EdTech industry has been surging in the past decade immensely, and according to a forecast, the Online Education market would be worth $286.62bn by 2023 with a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 10.26% from 2018 to 2023. The modern era of online education has enforced a lot in its growth and expansion beyond any limit. Due to having many dominant features like ease of information sharing, personalized learning experience, transparency of assessment, etc, it is now preferable to traditional education.

In the present scenario due to the Covid-19, the online education sector has witnessed rapid growth and is attracting a lot of new customers. Due to this rapid growth, many new companies have emerged in this industry. With the availability and ease of use of digital marketing resources, companies can reach out to a wider audience with their offerings. The customers who show interest in these offerings are termed as leads. There are various sources of obtaining leads for Edtech companies, like

  • The customer interacts with the marketing front on social media or other online platforms.
  • The customer browses the website/app and downloads the brochure
  • The customer connects through emails for more information.

The company then nurtures these leads and tries to convert them to paid customers. For this, the representative from the organization connects with the lead on call or through email to share further details.

Objective¶

ExtraaLearn is an initial stage startup that offers programs on cutting-edge technologies to students and professionals to help them upskill/reskill. With a large number of leads being generated on a regular basis, one of the issues faced by ExtraaLearn is to identify which of the leads are more likely to convert so that they can allocate resources accordingly. You, as a data scientist at ExtraaLearn, have been provided the leads data to:

  • Analyze and build an ML model to help identify which leads are more likely to convert to paid customers,
  • Find the factors driving the lead conversion process
  • Create a profile of the leads which are likely to convert

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of leads and their interaction details with ExtraaLearn. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • ID: ID of the lead
  • age: Age of the lead
  • current_occupation: Current occupation of the lead. Values include 'Professional','Unemployed',and 'Student'
  • first_interaction: How did the lead first interacted with ExtraaLearn. Values include 'Website', 'Mobile App'
  • profile_completed: What percentage of profile has been filled by the lead on the website/mobile app. Values include Low - (0-50%), Medium - (50-75%), High (75-100%)
  • website_visits: How many times has a lead visited the website
  • time_spent_on_website: Total time spent on the website
  • page_views_per_visit: Average number of pages on the website viewed during the visits.

  • last_activity: Last interaction between the lead and ExtraaLearn.

    • Email Activity: Seeking for details about program through email, Representative shared information with lead like brochure of program , etc
    • Phone Activity: Had a Phone Conversation with representative, Had conversation over SMS with representative, etc
    • Website Activity: Interacted on live chat with representative, Updated profile on website, etc

  • print_media_type1: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Newspaper.

  • print_media_type2: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Magazine.
  • digital_media: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn on the digital platforms.
  • educational_channels: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn in the education channels like online forums, discussion threads, educational websites, etc.
  • referral: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn through reference.
  • status: Flag indicating whether the lead was converted to a paid customer or not.

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
  • A few questions have been mentioned below which will help you approach the analysis in the right manner and generate insights from the data.
  • A thorough analysis of the data, in addition to the questions mentioned below, should be done.

Questions

  1. Leads will have different expectations from the outcome of the course and the current occupation may play a key role in getting them to participate in the program. Find out how current occupation affects lead status.
  2. The company's first impression on the customer must have an impact. Do the first channels of interaction have an impact on the lead status?
  3. The company uses multiple modes to interact with prospects. Which way of interaction works best?
  4. The company gets leads from various channels such as print media, digital media, referrals, etc. Which of these channels have the highest lead conversion rate?
  5. People browsing the website or mobile application are generally required to create a profile by sharing their personal data before they can access additional information.Does having more details about a prospect increase the chances of conversion?

Observations

  • The average age of leads is ~46 years with the youngest age being 18 years and oldest being 63 years. This indicates diversity of ages. The median age is 51 years. Majority of the leads (75%) are aged between 18 - 57 years. This indicate that majority of the leads are in their active working age. These are people who are likely to show interest in online learning.
  • The average website visits is ~4 with maximum being 30. Half of the leads have only visited 3 times. 75% had visited less than or equal 5 times. This indicates that only 25% had visited the website greater than 5 times. This may suggest low activity on the website by a majority of users.
  • There is a wide dispersion between the time spent on the websites by different leads. While the minimum is 0, the highest is 2,537.
  • There is little variation in the page_views_per_visit as indicated by the standard deviation of ~2. However, 25% of the dataset had views from 4 to 18 than the majority of the leads at 75th percentile with view at just 3.75
  • The status column shows that at least 50% of the leads did not lead to paid customers. This is indcative of low lead conversion rate.
Visualizing the distribution¶
In [220]:
# Function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None, color="violet", palette="winter"):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(nrows=2, sharex=True, 
                                           gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},figsize=figsize)                   
    
    # show title for the plot with summary statistics
    f2.suptitle(
        f"{str(feature).capitalize()} - \
        Skew:  {data[feature].skew().round(2)} \
        | Mean:  {data[feature].mean().round(2)} \
        | Median:  {data[feature].median()}")
    
    # Boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color=color)
    
    # Histogram
    if bins:
        sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette=palette)
    else:
        sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2)
    
    # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle ="--")
            
    # Add median to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-")

Observations

  • Age peaked between 50 - 60 years and has no outliers. This indicates that there are more leads/customers close to 60 years. This probably is the reason the median age is 51 years.
  • The distribution of the website visits is right skewed, though it peaked between 0 - 5 visits. There are lots of outliers in website visits.
  • Time spent on website is right skewed with no outliers. This indicates that most people spend about the same average time browsing the site.
  • Most people had around 2.5 page views per visit but large page views by few persons are also prevalent. The boxplot confirms this with some outliers to the right. This shows that customers shows different degrees of interest in the website.
  • Less than half of the leads are turned to paying customers. This indicates that majority of leads did not progress their interest to become paying customers.

# Function to plot stacked bar plots

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target, y_label):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins = True, normalize='index').sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False)
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 20)
    
    # visualize stacked bar chat
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False)
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1), frameon=True)
    plt.ylabel(y_label)
    plt.show()

Splitting of data into train and test¶

Splitting the data into 70% train and 30% test set

Some classification problems can exhibit a large imbalance in the distribution of the target classes: for instance there could be several times more negative samples than positive samples. In such cases it is recommended to use the stratified sampling technique to ensure that relative class frequencies are approximately preserved in each train and validation fold.

In [237]:
test_size = 0.3
random_state = 1

# call the train_test_split function on the dataset
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = \
            train_test_split(x, y, test_size=test_size, shuffle=True, stratify=y, random_state=random_state)

  • Decision Tree gives more significance to the dominant class based on weightage. Hence, we need to pass a dictionary of the hyperparameter class_weight to the Decision Tree Class in order to take account of this.
In [244]:
# Get the weight of each class
wt_class_0 = np.round(data[data[status]==0].shape[0]/data.shape[0], 2) # Weight of class 0 
wt_class_1 = np.round(1 - wt_class_0, 2) # Weight of class 1

class_weight = {0:wt_class_0, 1:wt_class_1}

Model Evaluation¶

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

The model can make two types of wrong predictions:

  1. Predicting that a lead will convert to a paying customer when it does not - False Positive (FP).
  2. Predicting that a lead will not convert to a paying customer when it actually does - False Negative (FN).

Which case is more important?

  • For this project, predicting that a lead will convert when it actually does not (FP) is most important to us; in which case, we would be wasting our efforts at the least promising prospects instead of the promising prospects. This would be an important miss for the predictor and hence must be considered when evaluating the model performance.

  • How to reduce False Positives: The company would want to maximize the Recall criterion. The greater the Recall, the greater the chance of minimizing false positives. This will ultimately increase the chance of identifying the true positives and help the company identify the actions to increase the lead conversion rate.

Model Evaluation Function for all Models¶

In [245]:
# Model Evaluation Function to avoid repeating the code
def metrics_score(actual, predicted):
    print("Classification Report")
    print(classification_report(actual, predicted))

    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
    
    classes = ['Not Convert (-)', 'Convert (+)']
    plt.title("Confusion Matrix")
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels=classes, yticklabels=classes)
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

Function to view feature importance¶

In [246]:
# Re-usable function for viewing important features
def plot_importance(model):
    f_importances = model.feature_importances_
    columns = x.columns
    
    col_importance = "importance" # name of `importance` column
    col_cum_importance = 'cum_importance' # name of `cumulative importance` column
    
    df_importance = pd.DataFrame(
        data=f_importances, index=columns, columns=[col_importance]).sort_values(by=col_importance, \
                                                                               ascending=False)
    df_importance[col_cum_importance] = df_importance[col_importance].cumsum() # Add cummulative importance
    print(df_importance)
    print('-' * 50)
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
    sns.barplot(x=df_importance[col_importance], y=df_importance.index);

    #Plot the DT

               feature_names=features, filled=True, class_names=class_names, node_ids=True, fontsize=12);

Do we need to prune the tree?¶

A Decision tree that is trained to its full depth will highly likely lead to overfitting the training data - therefore Pruning is important. In simpler terms, the aim of Decision Tree Pruning is to construct an algorithm that will generalize better on test data.

**The tree needs pruning because it overfits on the training data and unable to generalize on the test data.

In [254]:
# Tuning of the Decision Tree
dt_tuned_classifier = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=random_state) #Tuned Object of the Decision Tree

# Grid of parameters to choose from
df_parameters = {
    "max_depth": [5, 7, None],        
    "max_features": [None, 0.8, 1],
    "random_state": [None, random_state, 0],
    "class_weight": [None, class_weight, {0: wt_class_1, 1: wt_class_0}]
             }

# Run the grid search
dt_grid_obj = GridSearchCV(dt_tuned_classifier, df_parameters, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error', cv=5)

dt_grid_obj = dt_grid_obj.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Set the dt_tuned_classifier to the best combination of parameters
dt_tuned_classifier = dt_grid_obj.best_estimator_

dt_tuned_classifier.fit(x_train, y_train)

Building a Random Forest Model¶

  • Random Forest is a bagging algorithm where the base models are Decision Trees. Samples are taken from the training data and on each sample, a decision tree makes a prediction.
  • The results from all the decision trees are combined and the final prediction is made using voting (for classification problems) or averaging (for regression problems).**

The Random Forest estimator performs poorly on the test data due to overfitting. The tree will need to be pruned to obtain better results. This guarantees that the predictor will perform better on unseen data.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

Insights¶

  1. The greatest factor to consider in order to improve lead conversion rate is Time Spent on Website by potential customers.
  2. Applying the Pareto 80/20 principle, factors which offers the greatest potential at converting leads to paying customers are: Time Spent on website, first interaction - website, profile completion rate - medium, age, last activity by phone and the unemployed.
  3. Time Spent on website, first interaction - website account for more than 50% in terms of importance.
  4. The media platforms have not added much significance to lead conversion rate. This can be boosted.

Recommendations¶

  • The company should follow up with leads who have spent much time on the website. This should go with the page views per visit in order to filter out those may just be idling on the website without actually viewing.
  • The first channel should have maximum impact on the customers. Special attention should be paid to the website, its interface, attraction and appeal to the customers.
  • The company should utilize more Search Engine Optimization (SEO) in order to drive more people to have their first interaction with the online course through the web.
  • Potential customers who have not considerably filled their profile greater than 50% should be followed up.
  • Potential customers who are unemployed and have spent much time on the website should be followed up and probably offered personalized discount due to their reduced ability to pay. They are likely to show more interest in online course in order to upskill for their next job.
  • The media channels are not adding much in terms of conversion rate. They should be investigated and re-energized for better penetration. One are of media that easily scale is the digital media.
  • The company should encourage referral in order to boost enrolment. Potential customers tend to trust words from their friends, family or acquaintances more. The referral programme could be incentivitized to encourage more of it.
